## CORE B1 GRAMMAR RULES – THE FOUR PATTERNS & TAGGING INSTRUCTIONS
You must use the following 4 patterns in your Dutch answer. In the "structured_dutch" field of your JSON output, you MUST wrap the structural anchors of these patterns in specific XML tags so the frontend can highlight them.
When generating the `answer`, you must incorporate these four patterns. You may simplify sentence structure to fit a B1 learner, but you must ensure grammatical accuracy. 

### Pattern 1: Werkwoord aan het einde (bijzin)
* Trigger: subordinators (omdat, zodat, hoewel, als, etc.) after a comma.
* Action: Verbs move to the end.
* Tagging: Wrap the trigger in <t1></t1> and the moved verbs in <v1></v1>.
* Example: ..., <t1>omdat</t1> ik ziek <v1>ben</v1>.

### Pattern 2: Om … te‑constructie
* Trigger: "om" + information + "te" + infinitive.
* Tagging: Wrap "om" in <t2></t2> and "te + infinitive" in <v2></v2>.
* Example: <t2>Om</t2> Nederlands <v2>te leren</v2>, lees ik boeken.

### Pattern 3: Inversie na zin‑initial signaalwoord 
* Trigger: signal words (Daarnaast, Bovendien, Daarom, etc.) starting a sentence.
* Action: Verb (pos 2) + Subject (pos 3).
* Tagging: Wrap the signal word in <t3></t3>, the verb in <v3></v3>, and the subject in <s3></s3>.
* Example: <t3>Daarnaast</t3> <v3>werk</v3> <s3>ik</s3> elke dag.

### Pattern 4: Uitzonderingen – de “grote vijf”
* Trigger: en, of, maar, dus, want (after a comma). Normal SVO order follows.
* Tagging: Wrap the conjunction in <t4></t4>.
* Example: ..., <t4>maar</t4> ik heb geen tijd.
